<HEADLINE>
CERTIFIED TEACHERS ONLY HALF HIRED AS REGULAR FACULTY MEMBERS
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taipei,  April  10 (CNA) 04/10/07  21:37:33 (By Elizabeth Hsu)
</P>
<P>
Only 54 percent of more than 125,000 certified teachers currently
work a regular faculty members in public schools of all kinds,
excluding colleges and universities, around Taiwan in 2007,
according to a report released Tuesday by the Ministry of
Education.
</P>
<P>
The annual report on teacher cultivation indicated that 46,154 of
the persons holding official teaching certificates, or 36
percent, were not serve at any schools last year.
</P>
<P>
Professor Kuo Lung-hsin of National Taiwan Normal University, who
is one of the authors of the report, opined that adeclining birth
has resulted in a decreasing demand for teachers in elementary
schools in the past years, and that the situation is likely to
worsen with the number of enrollees in elementary schools around
the country expected to drop to 190,000 in the 2012 academic
year, down from 290,000 in 2006.
</P>
